snippet.textDisplay: OK I am sorry, but throughout this whole video this woman has been disappointing me since the beginning. To start, Mark did not mean to interrupt her for all she knows he may have had a question and when learning the art of combat it is more important to ask questions than follow orders because asking questions allows you to get a better understanding of what you're doing so you don't harm yourself or anyone around you, the 10 push ups thing is weak, what real martial arts do is have you do a difficult training exercise to improve your skills. Second, she told him never to say sorry, that is also incorrect. Mark and Ethan are both unsure of what they are doing and Mark tends to try to jump the gun alot we all no this, sorry Mark no offense, and he was eager to get started on what he was learning. He apologized for getting ahead because he realized "hey I don't know exactly what I'm doing, I should slow down and pay attention to what's going on so I can do this correctly and avoid injuring myself and anyone around me. Third, the bow is far from the oldest weapon known to man, the oldest weapon on earth is the stone because without the stone it would not be possible to cut and carve a stick to make a perfect fully functional bow. The bow is a highly skilled weapon and takes some people years maybe even decades to master. But those who have and are able to master a bow, nothing can stand against that. In martial arts, especially the weapons combat part of it, asking questions, following instructions as well as you can, learning everything you possibly can and doing your best is what makes you become stronger in the since of weaponry. Now Mark said who did it better in the sense of who bent the bow and hooked the string better. In martial arts there is no such thing as no competition, what they did is called boasting and boasting is something that martial artists frown upon for many reasons. Competition is good, but when you challenge someone to a spar you are asking the person you're challenging, hey can you come help me so I can see and learn what I know and what I need to get better at and the one you challenge should be the same. There's always room for improvement, that's why we challenge ourselves to become better simple as that

snippet.textDisplay:
If anyone wondering why the arrows are constantly going to the right, it's because they're not controlling the archers paradox. Basically, modern bows have a "shelf" in the riser (the handle) for the arrows to be lined up with the string and target, whereas these traditional reflex bows they're using don't, so the arrows stick out at an angle to the right, and therefore the arrows travels to the right. Traditional archers would control this by adjusting the tension on their index finger on the string to "bend the arrow" to the centre of the target.

By the way, these historic bows are nothing compared to modern day compound bows, which have an unbeatable amount of power and accuracy, and are used by hunters and special forces worldwide.

Yeah I'm a compound guy.
